posts.body:
https://archive.vn/aPHFQ
https://www.whonix.org/wiki/Kicksecure
https://www.whonix.org/wiki/SecBrowser

Privacy and Fingerprinting Resistance

Research from a pool of 500,000 Internet users has shown that the vast majority (84%) have unique browser configurations and version information which makes them trackable across the Internet. When Java or Flash is installed, this figures rises to 94%.[12] SecBrowser â„¢ shares the fingerprint with around three million [archive] other Tor Browser users, which allows people who use SecBrowser â„¢ to "blend in" with the larger population and better protect their privacy.

The EFF has found [archive] that while most browsers are uniquely fingerprintable, resistance is afforded via four methods:

    Disabling JavaScript with tools like NoScript.
    Use of Torbutton, which is bundled with SecBrowser â„¢ and enabled by default.
    Use of mobile devices like Android and iPhone.
    Corporate desktop machines which are clones of one another.

With JavaScript disabled, SecBrowser â„¢ provides significant resistance to browser fingerprinting.[13]

    The User Agent is uniform for all Torbutton users.
    Plugins are blocked.
    The screen resolution is rounded down to 50 pixel multiples.
    The timezone is set to GMT.
    DOM Storage is cleared and disabled.

The EFF's Panopticlick [archive] fingerprint test shows that SecBrowser â„¢ resists fingerprinting.

Note: Because tracking techniques are complex, Panopticlick does not measure all forms of tracking and protection.

    SecBrowser â„¢ conveys 6.26 bits of identifying information.
    One in 76.46 browsers have the same fingerprint.
    Browsers that convey lower bits of identification are better at resisting fingerprinting.[14]

When Tor Browser's and SecBrowser â„¢'s HTTP headers are compared using Fingerprint central's test suite [archive] the results are near identical.

posts.subject: We've all been behind troublesome customers
posts.body:
And most store owners accept such unpleasantness as just "part of the job".

But there comes a point, where the customer isn't worth it. So any shop owner must have the right to eject and ban customers they just don't want.

The government should have no role in these decisions.

posts.subject: As a rule.....
posts.body:
niggers just aren't worth it as customers. Too much work and the possibility of a negative return.

It would be great if black business stepped up to the plate and addressed this market entirely....Not a burden others want.
